  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "And, moreover, he set captains of war over the people, i.e., the populace of Jerusalem, assembled them in the open space at the city gate (which gate is not stated; cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 8:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 8:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and addressed them in encouraging words; cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 30:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". On ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 32:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 20:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 31:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc. \"For with us is more than with him.\" רב, quite general, the closer definition following in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 32:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " : \"With him is an arm of flesh; but with us is Jahve, our God, to help us.\" An arm of flesh  equals  frail human power; cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 21:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " : their (the Egyptians') horses are flesh, not spirit; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 17:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 56:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". \"And the people leaned themselves on (i.e., trusted in) the words of Hezekiah.\" These statements are not inconsistent with the account in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 18:14-16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", that Hezekiah began to negotiate with the Assyrian king Sennacherib when he had begun to take the fenced cities of the land unto Lachish, promised to pay him tribute, and actually paid the sum demanded, employing for that purpose even the sheet gold on the temple doors. These negotiations are passed over, not only in our narrative, but also in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 36",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", because they had no influence upon the after course and the issue of the war. Sennacherib was not induced to withdraw by the payment of the sum demanded, and soon after the receipt of it he sent a detachment from Lachish against Jerusalem, to summon the city to surrender. The fortification of Jerusalem which the Chronicle records began before these negotiations, and was continued while they were in progress. ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
